title: Hard Drive Adaptor
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Parametric 3/4 Height 3.5inch to Full Height Hard Drive Adaptor.
Full height 3.5 inch drives are becoming increasingly difficult to source, and some slot in drive bays (e.g. Drobo) can allow a wobble which can put strain on the drive connector over time, when a 3/4 height drive is used.  This makes the Drobo or drive prone to serious damage.
This solves that problem, with an adaptor that fits on top to make the drive full height.
If there's not enough space around the drive for cooling, you may have to create holes in this design for cooling.
Print on a Replicator.  Use Sugru to attach to the hard drive in the 4 corners as shown in the pictures.

comments.text: I tried printing this on my Printrbot Simple with 1.75mm pla. but it came out leaning to the left. Did you use Repetier-Host with Slic3r to print yours or some other program? Any idea what can cause this? I have run across this with a few other files too. Any help would be appreciated. Thanks
comments.author: Grimarr

comments.text:
I'm using slic3r 1.0.0RC3 set to Reprap(marlin/sprinter/repetier). I printed with 3mm, but 1.75 should be fine so long as your slic3r is set correctly.
I'm be curious if you can print a simple cube, and a simple cylinder without any distortion. Leaning can mean that a movement on one axis is getting slightly offset on each iteration (loose belt or pulley/cable).
Also, if you preview your print within pronterface you can see if the gcode is telling the printer to print at an angle, or if it is something with your printer - likely that is the issue.

I was having trouble with the original model crashing my slicers. I was able to use Netfabb to resize the file and recenter him (he was huge). I also flattened out his feet so he can be stuck directly to the print bed.   
The model had a number of self intersections that caused my slicer to add gaps and put in solid surfaces and he just kinda feel apart. After a run through the Netfabb cloud he lost a little hair, I tried but was unable to get it to stop removing the two outside shells. It's not a deal breaker to me, you could always try to put them back in.  
He of course requires support, and if you use fully auto support generation you may end up with some supports between his shell and his body, there is a gap towards the top just above his arm that goes all the way across. I used the manual support generation in Simplify 3D to remove this before printing.
